               <persName corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Mǝrč̣ā Warqe</persName>
              <persName xml:lang="en" corresp="#n1">M. Warkee</persName>
               <persName><roleName type="title">liqa makʷās</roleName></persName>
               <persName><roleName type="title">lǝǧ</roleName></persName>
               <occupation type="political"/>
               <birth when="1825"/>
               <floruit>He was one of the first foreign-educated Ethiopians who acted as a diplomat, secretary and interpreter.
Mǝrč̣ā Warqe received his education at the British missionary school of John Wilson in <placeName ref="LOC1956Bombay">Bombay</placeName>.
In <date>1849</date> he left India and founded a school in <placeName ref="LOC1264Adwa"/> together with his
brother <persName ref="PRS4398GabruWa"/>. Later, Mǝrč̣ā Warqe became a follower of <persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros"/>.
He played a crucial political role during the British military compaign led by <persName ref="PRS7484Napier"/>.
Mǝrč̣ā Warqe established contact between <persName ref="PRS7484Napier"/> and <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"/>,
thus securing support for <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"/> after the downfall of <persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros"/>.
In <date>1875</date> Mǝrč̣ā Warqe was an envoy of <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"/> in <placeName ref="LOC2085Cairo"/>.
In <date>1884</date> he acted as a secretary of <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"/>, and in <date>1896</date> he served as
an interpreter for <persName ref="PRS6668Mangasa"/>.
               </floruit>
               <death notBefore="1896"/>
            </person>
